Hey team 👋

Most of us have been working closely with LLMs — feeding JSON configs, API responses, and schema files into ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot and similar tools. By now we've all felt the friction of large JSON eating up context window space just through structural noise — brackets, quotes, repeated key names across every array row.

TOON (Token-Optimized Object Notation) has been gaining traction as a practical solution to exactly that. It's a compact, human-readable format that strips away the overhead while keeping every value intact and fully readable by the model.

I built a VS Code extension around it — JSON to TOON Converter (v1.0.2) — so we don't have to rely on external websites or third-party tools to do the conversion. Everything runs natively inside VS Code. Your data never leaves your machine.

What it does

It converts JSON into TOON — a compact, quote-free format that cuts structural noise: no repeated brackets, no redundant key names across every row, no surrounding quotes.

Real numbers from the extension's own benchmark:

JSON: 665 characters / ~92 tokens
TOON: 237 characters / ~41 tokens
55% fewer tokens. Same data.
On large API responses or deeply nested config files the savings are significantly higher.

Three ways to use it — all inside VS Code, no extra tools

CodeLens — a → Convert to TOON link appears inline above line 1 of any JSON file. Just click it.
Right-click — works in the editor and in the Explorer panel. Right-click any .json file → Convert to TOON.
Command Palette — Ctrl+Shift+P / Cmd+Shift+P → Convert to TOON.
Output panel

After converting, a panel opens with live before/after stats (lines, characters, estimated LLM tokens), syntax highlighting that matches your VS Code theme, a one-click Copy button, and a Save as .toon option.

Install

